<table>
<thead><tr><th>Plan</th><th>Cursor</th><th>Windsurf</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td><strong>Free</strong></td><td>2,000 completions/mo, 50 premium requests</td><td>Limited completions and Cascade usage</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Pro</strong></td><td>$20/mo — unlimited completions, 500 premium requests, Agent mode</td><td>$20/mo — unlimited completions, Cascade, Arena mode</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Max / Ultra</strong></td><td>N/A</td><td>$200/mo — unlimited premium models, priority support</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Teams / Business</strong></td><td>$40/user/mo — admin controls, privacy mode</td><td>$40/user/mo — centralized billing, team insights</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<h2>Recent Developments (2026)</h2>

<h3>Windsurf's March 2026 Pricing Shakeup</h3>
<p>In March 2026, Windsurf replaced its credit-based system with a fixed quota model and raised Pro from $15 to $20/month — matching Cursor. This removed the pricing advantage and simplified the choice to feature fit rather than cost.</p>

<h3>Windsurf Acquisition by Cognition</h3>
<p>Industry reports from April 2026 suggest Windsurf was acquired by Cognition AI (the company behind Devin, the autonomous coding agent). This could mean deeper AI agent integration and enterprise features in future Windsurf releases — or it could signal strategy shifts. Worth watching if you're making a long-term commitment.</p>

<h3>Cursor's Continued Incremental Improvement</h3>
<p>Rather than dramatic pivots, Cursor has steadily improved its Agent mode, expanded model support (adding Claude Opus 4, GPT-5), and refined its codebase indexing. It remains the more conservative, reliable choice.</p>

<h2>Which One Should You Choose?</h2>

<p><strong>Choose Cursor if:</strong> You're a professional developer working on production code. You need reliable agent mode, full VS Code extension compatibility, and battle-tested performance. You value speed and precision in tab completion over experimental features.</p>

<p><strong>Choose Windsurf if:</strong> You want an AI that learns your patterns and improves over time. You like experimenting with different models via Arena mode. You're working on projects where persistent context (Flows) saves you significant mental overhead. You're willing to trade some maturity for innovation.</p>

<p><strong>Consider both if:</strong> You can afford both subscriptions ($40/mo total). Use Windsurf for exploratory coding and long refactoring sessions, Cursor for production work and when you need rock-solid extension support.</p>

<h2>Final Verdict</h2>
<p>At the same $20/month price point, the Cursor vs Windsurf decision is genuinely close — closer than it was a year ago. Cursor remains the safer choice for professional developers who need reliability and ecosystem support. Windsurf is the more innovative platform for developers who value contextual awareness and experimentation.</p>

<p>For most developers in 2026, we recommend starting with Cursor's free tier, trying Windsurf's free tier alongside it, and seeing which one feels more natural for your workflow. The good news: both are excellent tools, and choosing either will make you significantly more productive than using traditional IDEs.</p>

